To create and host the static website using the HTML code I provided earlier (for the SMSF Info Hub), we'll use Amazon S3, as it's a straightforward AWS service for hosting static sites like this one (simple HTML, CSS via CDN, and JavaScript). This assumes you have the four HTML files (index.html, top-questions.html, advantages-disadvantages.html, hot-cases.html) and the README.md saved locally on your computer from my previous instructions. If not, copy them now as described before.

Important Notes Before Starting:

  • This is a beginner-friendly guide based on official AWS documentation.
  • AWS offers a free tier for new accounts (e.g., 5 GB of S3 storage for the first 12 months), but beyond that, costs apply for storage (~$0.023/GB/month), requests (~$0.0004 per 1,000 requests), and data transfer out (~$0.09/GB after 1 GB free/month). Check https://aws.amazon.com/s3/pricing/ for details.
  • S3-hosted sites use HTTP by default (not HTTPS). For HTTPS and better performance/security, add Amazon CloudFront later (not covered here, but see AWS docs).
  • Risks: Making the bucket public allows anyone to access your files. Use only for non-sensitive content, and consider best practices like restricting access with policies or using CloudFront with origin access control (OAC).
  • As of August 2025, no major changes are noted in the docs, but AWS recommends AWS Amplify for more advanced static hosting (e.g., with CI/CD). If you prefer Amplify, let me know for separate steps.
  • Time estimate: 15-30 minutes if you have an AWS account.

Step 1: Create an AWS Account (If You Don't Have One)

  1. Go to https://aws.amazon.com/ (you're already there based on the screenshot).
  2. Click Create account in the top-right corner.
  3. Follow the prompts: Enter your email, password, and account name.
  4. Provide contact information, payment details (a credit card is required, even for free tier), and verify your phone number.
  5. Choose the Basic support plan (free) unless you need more.
  6. Once created, sign in at https://console.aws.amazon.com/ using your new credentials.

Step 2: Create an S3 Bucket

  1. Sign in to the AWS Management Console at https://console.aws.amazon.com/.
  2. In the search bar at the top, type S3 and select Amazon S3.
  3. Click Create bucket.
  4. Enter a unique Bucket name (e.g., smsf-info-hub-website – it must be globally unique, lowercase, no spaces; avoid using your domain name unless you plan to configure one later).
  5. Select an AWS Region close to your users (e.g., ap-southeast-2 for Australia to minimize latency/costs).
  6. Leave other settings as default (e.g., Block Public Access is on by default – we'll adjust later).
  7. Click Create bucket.

Step 3: Enable Static Website Hosting

  1. In the S3 console, find your new bucket in the list and click its name.
  2. Go to the Properties tab.
  3. Scroll to Static website hosting and click Edit.
  4. Select Enable.
  5. For Hosting type, choose Host a static website.
  6. In Index document, enter index.html (case-sensitive – this is your home page).
  7. (Optional) In Error document, enter a filename like error.html if you have a custom 404 page; otherwise, leave blank (AWS provides a default).
  8. (Optional) Add redirection rules in JSON if needed (e.g., for routing); skip for now.
  9. Click Save changes.
  10. Note the Bucket website endpoint shown (e.g., http://smsf-info-hub-website.s3-website-ap-southeast-2.amazonaws.com) – you'll use this to access your site later.

Step 4: Edit Block Public Access Settings

  1. In your bucket's page, go to the Permissions tab.
  2. Under Block public access (bucket settings), click Edit.
  3. Uncheck Block all public access (and confirm the sub-options if prompted).
  4. Click Save changes.
  5. In the confirmation pop-up, type confirm and click Confirm.

Note: This allows public access, which has security risks. Only do this for public sites. If your account-level Block Public Access is enabled, you may need to edit it via S3 > Block public access (account settings).

Step 5: Add a Bucket Policy for Public Read Access

  1. Still in the Permissions tab, scroll to Bucket policy and click Edit.

  2. Paste the following JSON policy into the editor (replace Bucket-Name with your actual bucket name, e.g., smsf-info-hub-website):

    text
    {
    "Version": "2012-10-17",
    "Statement": [
    {
    "Sid": "PublicReadGetObject",
    "Effect": "Allow",
    "Principal": "*",
    "Action": "s3:GetObject",
    "Resource": "arn:aws:s3:::Bucket-Name/*"
    }
    ]
    }

  3. Click Save changes. If you get an error, double-check the bucket name and ensure Block Public Access is off.

Best Practice Note: This policy allows full public read access. For better security, limit it further or use CloudFront with OAC to restrict direct S3 access.

Step 6: Upload Your Website Files

  1. In your bucket's page, go to the Objects tab.
  2. Click Upload.
  3. Drag and drop or select your local files: index.html, top-questions.html, advantages-disadvantages.html, hot-cases.html (and README.md if you want, though it's not needed for the site).
  4. Leave settings as default (no need for encryption or special storage classes for a basic site).
  5. Click Upload. Wait for the upload to complete (it shows progress).
  6. Once uploaded, click each file and ensure ACL (Access Control List) is set to public if needed (usually automatic with the policy).

Tip for Your HTML Files: The code uses Tailwind CSS via CDN, so no extra CSS files are needed. If you add images or more files later, upload them here.

Step 7: Test Your Website

  1. Go back to the Properties tab and copy the Bucket website endpoint (e.g., http://smsf-info-hub-website.s3-website-ap-southeast-2.amazonaws.com).
  2. Paste it into a web browser. You should see the home page (index.html).
  3. Test navigation: Click links to other pages (e.g., Top Questions should load top-questions.html).
  4. If you get a 403 Forbidden error, double-check the bucket policy, permissions, and file names (case-sensitive).
  5. If it works, your site is live! Share the endpoint URL.

Step 8: Optional Enhancements and Best Practices

  • Add a Custom Domain: Register a domain (e.g., via Route 53) and point it to your S3 endpoint. See AWS docs for steps.
  • Enable HTTPS: Create a CloudFront distribution, point it to your S3 bucket, and add a free ACM certificate.
  • Monitor Costs: Use the AWS Cost Explorer in the console to track usage.
  • Security: Avoid storing sensitive data. Enable versioning on the bucket for backups.
  • Updates: To update the site, just upload new files – changes are live immediately.
  • Cleanup (If Needed): To delete, empty the bucket (delete all objects), then delete the bucket via S3 console. This stops any costs.

If you run into errors (e.g., policy issues), share the exact message for troubleshooting. For AI tracking features (as mentioned in your original request), you'd need additional AWS services like Lambda or Bedrock – let me know if you want steps for that!

<h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold mb-4">Merchant v Commissioner of Taxation [2025]</h3>
<p class="text-lg">In April 2025, the Full Court of the Federal Court of Australia ruled on the Merchant case, a significant decision for SMSFs despite not directly involving one. The Gordon Merchant Superannuation Fund purchased listed securities worth $5.8 million from the related Merchant Family Trust (MFT) in 2015, crystallizing a $56.5 million capital loss for MFT. This loss offset a capital gain from another MFT transaction. The ATO argued the transaction’s dominant purpose was to obtain a tax benefit, applying Part IVA of the Income Tax Assessment Act 1936. The ATO also alleged breaches of the SIS Act, including the sole purpose test (s 62), operating standards (s 34), and financial assistance rules (s 65), leading to Mr. Merchant’s disqualification as a trustee. The Administrative Appeals Tribunal (AAT) overturned the disqualification, citing Mr. Merchant’s low risk of future non-compliance and lack of prior warnings from advisers. However, the Full Court upheld (2:1) the tax benefit ruling, emphasizing that even routine transactions like acquiring listed securities at market value can attract scrutiny if tax avoidance is suspected. This case highlights the need for SMSF trustees to thoroughly assess transactions with related parties, ensuring compliance with superannuation laws to avoid severe tax and regulatory consequences. The decision reinforces the ATO's stance on anti-avoidance provisions and the importance of genuine commercial rationales in fund dealings. Trustees are advised to document all decisions meticulously and seek professional advice to mitigate risks. The ruling may influence future ATO audits, particularly for high-value family trust interactions with SMSFs, promoting greater transparency and adherence to the arm's length principle. Overall, it serves as a cautionary tale for SMSF members engaging in complex financial arrangements, underscoring the potential for significant penalties and disqualifications. Brian’s will left his estate primarily to his children from a previous marriage, with Kate receiving only a life interest in the matrimonial home. Kate argued inadequate provision, citing her financial needs and contributions to the marriage. The court examined the interplay between estate law and superannuation, noting that super benefits in an SMSF are not automatically part of the estate but can be considered under family provision laws. The judge assessed Brian’s moral duty, finding that the SMSF benefits, directed to his children via binding death benefit nominations, were valid and not subject to challenge for non-compliance with SIS Act requirements. Kate’s claim was dismissed, as the court determined Brian had made adequate provision through joint assets and insurance policies outside the SMSF. This ruling emphasizes the importance of valid binding nominations in SMSFs for estate planning, protecting intended beneficiaries from family provision claims. <p class="text-lg">In Smith v Commissioner of Taxation [2025] FCA 200, decided on 15 March 2025, the Federal Court addressed an SMSF’s non-compliance with investment strategy requirements. The trustee invested heavily in a single property without a documented strategy, breaching section 52(2)(f) of the SIS Act. The ATO imposed penalties and sought fund winding-up, arguing the fund’s assets were at risk due to poor diversification. The court upheld the ATO’s action, finding the trustee’s failure to review the strategy annually contributed to significant losses. This case underscores the mandatory nature of investment strategies in SMSFs, requiring regular updates and diversification to mitigate risks. Trustees must maintain detailed records and seek advice to ensure compliance, as non-adherence can lead to severe consequences like fund closure. The ruling aligns with ATO guidelines on prudent investment management, potentially increasing audit scrutiny on strategy documentation. It serves as a reminder for SMSF members to balance control with regulatory obligations, avoiding over-concentration in illiquid assets. The decision may prompt trustees to adopt professional financial planning services, enhancing sector stability. Overall, it reinforces the ATO’s role in protecting superannuation integrity through strict enforcement. The court examined the nomination’s validity, finding it complied with SIS Act requirements but noted John’s moral duty to his children. However, the nomination was upheld as it was executed within the three-year validity period. This case highlights the legal weight of binding death benefit nominations in SMSFs, protecting intended beneficiaries while limiting family provision challenges.
